         <div xml:id="main">
            <head type="incipit">
               <supplied reason="XTF-compatibility">These blueflowered Andersonias would have travelled  ¶ quite safely in the Wards Case ¶  had the lid been occasionally lifted, had the moisture been kept properly adjusted through attention during the...</supplied>
            </head>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="number" xml:lang="en">81.12.30</p>
            <p rend="correspondent" xml:lang="en">To [Joseph Hooker]</p>
            <p rend="location" xml:lang="en">RBG Kew, Kew Correspondence, Australia, Mueller, 1871-81, f. 329.</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 0in; margin-right: 0.3516in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <note xml:id="ftn1" type="footnote" n="1">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>The MS is on the back of a printed Kew report form, dated 28 September 1881. The report was perhaps enclosed with J. Hooker to M, 25 September 1881. The report, on a Wardian case of plants said to have arrived at Kew on 27 September 1881, stated:</p>
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Several roots of grass-like plant - possibly may grow.</p>
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
                     <seg style="">Dead plants</seg>
                  </p>
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Various species of Epacrideae ?Styphelia</p>
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 9pt; margin-left: 0.5in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.5in; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>All quite dead and rotten. It is quite impossible for plants of this character to exist many days in a Wardian Case - Seeds therefore should be sent.</p>
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>The entry in the Kew Inwards Book, 1878-1883, has similar comments; see note 1 to M to J Hooker, 12 July 1881 (in this edition as 81-07-12a). </p>
               </note>These blueflowered <name key="Andersonia">Andersonia</name>s would have travelled <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">quite safely in the Wards Case</hi>
               </seg> had the lid been occasionally lifted, had the moisture been kept properly adjusted through attention during the voyage as requested, and had the plants been lifted in the cool season.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 0in; margin-right: 0.3516in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="en">F.v.M.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 0in; margin-right: 0.3516in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="en">30/12/81</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="plant%20names" xml:lang="en">
               <name key="Andersonia">Andersonia</name>
            </p>
